  "text": "Theoretical guarantees about solution times for quantum algorithms (found in [CITATION_1] ) assume that the computation takes place in an ideal closed system, perfectly isolated from energy interference from ambient surroundings. The D-Wave 2X chip is housed in a highly shielded chamber and cooled to below 15mK; nevertheless as is the case with any real-world quantum device, it must suffer some amount of interference, which has the general effect of reducing the probability of landing in a ground state. Thus theoretical guarantees on performance may not apply to these systems. We consider any D-Wave processor to be a heuristic solver, which requires empirical approaches to performance analysis.",
